\begin_layout Section*
Predictability and balance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is need for different types of capacity as titles move through their
 life-cycles.
 As one title is released, the next one enters pipe-line.
 Tasks and competencies are too specialised, employees can not quickly be
 reassigned.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Risks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Losing employees
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Losing people may cause undercapacity at critical times.
 Losing key people may delay titles/projects by months, at worst.
 Bad leadership major cause.
 Thuss is the preventative strategy.
 Preventative strategies:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
promote good leadership
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Exchange/rotate successful leaders to spread culture
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Monitor for dissatisfaction; encourage culture open to criticism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Risk can be lower enough by internal strategies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Pipeline risks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Poor sales causes loss of revenue and contracts, which causes overcapacity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Long-term planning of titles
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Avoid up-scaling uncertain projects; look for ways to improve
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Offer over-capacity to other studios within EA
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Paragraph*
Highest impact
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
No definitive strategy can prevent or mitigate pipeline risks; a predictable
 pipeline is most important factor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Strategies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Integration upwards (publisher EA)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Benefits:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Predictability in pipeline
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Network of internal customers and suppliers; meet unpredictable demand
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Drawbacks:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
EA limits distribution channels to favour its own portal (Origin vs.
 Steam)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Integration downwards (tools)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Early access to technology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Opportunities occur for game studios to gain early access to new technology
 (consoles, graphics adapters and packages), integrations may occur downwards
 in the value chain.
 These benefit technology providers such as Sony and Apple as they are able
 to launch products with ready made games.
 There is a risk of overinvesting in technology which may not gain momentum.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Conclusions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Predictable demand is essential for a studio with very long cycle-times,
 as interruptions in the pipeline causes overcapacity (layoffs), dispersal
 of talent, and all related negative consequences.
 Undercapacity can be prevented by improved processes and planning, and
 sizing operations to allow certain variations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One possible strategy for a studio is to integrate upwards with the publisher.
 Benefits and drawbacks depend on the resources and network-effects the
 publisher can offer.
\end_layout

